From cou.: 0 Journal
From Soup: 0 Faraday Discuss.
 ###### 
From cou.: 1 We introduced a minimal model of the donor–acceptor interface encountered in organic solar cells to explain the efficient generation of free charges in these systems and we investigated the nature of charge transfer states formed by a delocalized exciton in the donor component. Contrarily to the generally accepted view excitons do not generate strongly bound hole-electron pairs, but relatively delocalized charge transfer states with energy very close to the energy of free holes and electrons. These states are kinetically more accessible from the exciton state and very close in structure to the free hole and electron states. The most relevant molecular parameter that affects the rate of exciton dissociation is the electronic coupling between donor orbitals and acceptor orbitals, i.e. the band widths of the donor and acceptor materials. Moreover, and to some surprise, we find that the process of charge separation is mostly a purely electronic process and a very similar physics can be described neglecting the role of nuclear degrees of freedom altogether.
From Soup: 1 We introduced a minimal model of the donor–acceptor interface encountered in organic solar cells to explain the efficient generation of free charges in these systems and we investigated the nature of charge transfer states formed by a delocalized exciton in the donor component. Contrarily to the generally accepted view excitons do not generate strongly bound hole-electron pairs, but relatively delocalized charge transfer states with energy very close to the energy of free holes and electrons. These states are kinetically more accessible from the exciton state and very close in structure to the free hole and electron states. The most relevant molecular parameter that affects the rate of exciton dissociation is the electronic coupling between donor orbitals and acceptor orbitals, i.e. the band widths of the donor and acceptor materials. Moreover, and to some surprise, we find that the process of charge separation is mostly a purely electronic process and a very similar physics can be described neglecting the role of nuclear degrees of freedom altogether.
 ###### 
From cou.: 2 The great technological interest in the development of organic solar cells has generated a good number of new problems of fundamental nature related to the charge and exciton generation and transport in these devices.1–5 In organic solar cells an electron donor (D) and an acceptor (A) organic material with suitable energy levels are put in contact. The absorption of solar radiation typically generates excitons in the electron donor. The exciton can dissociate at the interface between the donor and acceptor to generate free holes (in the donor) and electrons (in the acceptor), but the actual mechanism for the formation of free charges is not truly understood. Conventionally it is believed that, before dissociating, the exciton migrates near the interface where a bound charge transfer (CT) state is formed (see Fig. 1a). This state should subsequently generate free holes and electrons, but obviously this process is kinetically unfavourable and a bound CT state seems more likely to be destroyed by hole-electron recombination.6,7 The idea that a bound CT state is the intermediate between exciton and free charges seems not reconcilable with the experiments showing that most excitons generate free charges in good solar cells.8,9
From Soup: 2 The great technological interest in the development of organic solar cells has generated a good number of new problems of fundamental nature related to the charge and exciton generation and transport in these devices. 1–5 In organic solar cells an electron donor (D) and an acceptor (A) organic material with suitable energy levels are put in contact. The absorption of solar radiation typically generates excitons in the electron donor . The exciton can dissociate at the interface between the donor and acceptor to generate free holes (in the donor) and electrons (in the acceptor), but the actual mechanism for the formation of free charges is not truly understood. Conventionally it is believed that, before dissociating, the exciton migrates near the interface where a bound charge transfer (CT) state is formed (see Fig. 1a ). This state should subsequently generate free holes and electrons, but obviously this process is kinetically unfavourable and a bound CT state seems more likely to be destroyed by hole-electron recombination. 6,7 The idea that a bound CT state is the intermediate between exciton and free charges seems not reconcilable with the experiments showing that most excitons generate free charges in good solar cells. 8,9
 ###### 
From cou.: 3 A number of proposals have been put forward to explain the efficient generation of free charges. It was proposed, but a quantitative theory is still missing, that the excess energy generated when the bound CT state is formed from the exciton is not immediately dissipated in heat but it is used to promote the dissociation into free charges.10 Considering that some interfaces can develop an intrinsic interface dipole moment it was suggested that this is exploited to facilitate the charge separation process.11,12 Many authors have reached the conclusion that the delocalization of the charges in the CT state may reduce the barrier for generating free charges.13–16 Most importantly, device modelling seems to agree with electrical measurements if one could assume that exciton dissociation leads to relatively delocalized holes and electrons.17,18
From Soup: 3 A number of proposals have been put forward to explain the efficient generation of free charges. It was proposed, but a quantitative theory is still missing, that the excess energy generated when the bound CT state is formed from the exciton is not immediately dissipated in heat but it is used to promote the dissociation into free charges. 10 Considering that some interfaces can develop an intrinsic interface dipole moment it was suggested that this is exploited to facilitate the charge separation process. 11,12 Many authors have reached the conclusion that the delocalization of the charges in the CT state may reduce the barrier for generating free charges. 13–16 Most importantly, device modelling seems to agree with electrical measurements if one could assume that exciton dissociation leads to relatively delocalized holes and electrons. 17,18
 ###### 
From cou.: 4 To make progress with this problem one needs to identify what the nature of the CT state generated by the exciton is and, possibly, one should express the rate for the generation of such a CT state in terms of a few key system parameters. We have recently proposed a model for long range exciton separation in organic solar cell interfaces where we computed the likelihood that an exciton far from the interface can generate directly quasi-free electrons and holes without an intermediate state at the interface.19 In that work we made a number of assumptions on the nature of the disorder in the system that, while realistic, hide some of the interesting physics of the process. In this paper we study instead the absolute minimal Hamiltonian model that explains the efficient process of charge generation in organic solar cells.
From Soup: 4 To make progress with this problem one needs to identify what the nature of the CT state generated by the exciton is and, possibly, one should express the rate for the generation of such a CT state in terms of a few key system parameters. We have recently proposed a model for long range exciton separation in organic solar cell interfaces where we computed the likelihood that an exciton far from the interface can generate directly quasi-free electrons and holes without an intermediate state at the interface. 19 In that work we made a number of assumptions on the nature of the disorder in the system that, while realistic, hide some of the interesting physics of the process. In this paper we study instead the absolute minimal Hamiltonian model that explains the efficient process of charge generation in organic solar cells.
 ###### 
From cou.: 5 The key elements of our model are the explicit inclusion of the hole-electron interaction and the description in terms of multi-electron states instead of one-electron states (Fig. 1b). To introduce the main idea of this paper through an intuitive example, we can consider a system composed by a donor and two acceptor fragments (DAA). The initial state can be thought of as a state where the excitation resides on the donor (D*AA). There are two possible charge transfer states which are two linear combinations of states (D+A−A) and (D+AA−) where the charge is localized on the two different acceptors. Since the two CT states have rather different energies it is expected that one of the CT state will have a strong (D+A−A) character and the other CT state will have a strong (D+AA−) character. It is not possible to tell without a model which of the two states will be more likely to be formed because (D+A−A) is more strongly coupled to the initial state, but (D+AA−) is energetically closer to the initial state. The naïve picture that the exciton at the interface generates a bound hole-electron pair may be very misleading and we will see in this paper that the formation of CT states with larger hole-electron separation is often the most kinetically favoured product.
From Soup: 5 The key elements of our model are the explicit inclusion of the hole-electron interaction and the description in terms of multi-electron states instead of one-electron states ( Fig. 1b ). To introduce the main idea of this paper through an intuitive example, we can consider a system composed by a donor and two acceptor fragments (DAA). The initial state can be thought of as a state where the excitation resides on the donor (D*AA). There are two possible charge transfer states which are two linear combinations of states (D + A − A) and (D + AA − ) where the charge is localized on the two different acceptors. Since the two CT states have rather different energies it is expected that one of the CT state will have a strong (D + A − A) character and the other CT state will have a strong (D + AA − ) character. It is not possible to tell without a model which of the two states will be more likely to be formed because (D + A − A) is more strongly coupled to the initial state, but (D + AA − ) is energetically closer to the initial state. The naïve picture that the exciton at the interface generates a bound hole-electron pair may be very misleading and we will see in this paper that the formation of CT states with larger hole-electron separation is often the most kinetically favoured product.
 ###### 
From cou.: 6 We consider in this paper the highly idealized situation of two perfectly crystalline donor and acceptor materials sharing a defect-less interface. We consider the materials to be molecular materials so that the initial state is a Frenkel exciton in the donor (delocalized because there are no defects). We consider finite size clusters (of different sizes) in the absence of information on the actual delocalization length of the exciton. Apart from some simplifications introduced to limit the number of parameters, the model is representative of junctions realized from gas phase deposition,20 although it is more common that one of the phases is amorphous. Most of the conclusions of this paper, however, are immediately generalizable to more complicated and common interfaces.
From Soup: 6 We consider in this paper the highly idealized situation of two perfectly crystalline donor and acceptor materials sharing a defect-less interface. We consider the materials to be molecular materials so that the initial state is a Frenkel exciton in the donor (delocalized because there are no defects). We consider finite size clusters (of different sizes) in the absence of information on the actual delocalization length of the exciton. Apart from some simplifications introduced to limit the number of parameters, the model is representative of junctions realized from gas phase deposition, 20 although it is more common that one of the phases is amorphous. Most of the conclusions of this paper, however, are immediately generalizable to more complicated and common interfaces.
