From cou.: 101 P
From Soup: 101 If we indicate with k ( n )→( m ) the rate constant for the process from Ψ ( n ) FE to Ψ ( m ) CT , the total rate for the process of generating any CT state can be expressed as: Where , with k B T being the thermal energy. The Boltzmann factor implies that we are assuming equilibrium among the FE electronic states. The initial and final states are very weakly coupled (see below for a justification) and the rate constant can be evaluated from the theory of non-adiabatic electron transfer reactions. 31 The electron transfer is accompanied by a deformation in the equilibrium geometry of the molecule which is quantified by the parameter λ , known as the reorganization energy. If the nuclear modes can be treated classically the rate of charge transfer can be expressed by the Marcus equation: 31 where V nm is the electronic coupling between the initial and final states. In writing eqn (13) we have noted that the reorganization energy λ m depends on the final state states m (depending on the localization of the charge the reorganization energy may change). The combination of the two factors containing the term λ m are normally referred to as the Franck–Condon factor. When the reorganization energy in the molecular crystals is decomposed according to the nuclear modes that contribute to it, 32 it turns out that more than half of the reorganization energy is due to high frequency modes that cannot be treated classically. A more general expression taking into account the quantum nature of nuclear modes can be used but, as we will see in the result session, this is not really needed.
