From cou.: 103 E
From Soup: 103 Except when we have very small clusters of 1–4 sites, or when we consider very localized states, we have generally , i.e. the coupling V nm is always sufficiently small enough to allow the use of a perturbative expression, such as eqn (13) . It is evident from eqn (13)–(14) that the parameter V DA will only modulate the final rate (through its square) but has otherwise no effect on the physics that we wish to describe. For this reason V DA was set to the physically plausible value of 0.08 eV and left unchanged.
 ###### 
From cou.: 104 Fig. 3b also shows that CT excitons are more bound (more localized) for small coupling VD. If we consider that these states are originating from the interaction between quasi free hole and electron in the donor and acceptor material, larger coupling is associated with lighter effective masses and less localization. Several papers have successfully described the CT interface exciton in this way10,29,30 focusing mostly on the lowest energy CT states. Our task however is to describe the generation of any CT state from Frenkel excitons.
From Soup: 104 The reorganization energy is smaller for more delocalized states and it is approximately inversely proportional to the size of the system. 33 This has been verified computationally for polymers of different lengths, 34 for polyacenes of different sizes 35 and for a large set of conjugated molecules. 33 To incorporate this effect in the model we assumed that, for the computation of the rate k ( n )→( m ) , λ m decreases with the increase of delocalization of the charge in the CT state as λ m = λ 0 / P ( m ) , where P ( m ) is the number of molecules that share a positive or a negative charge as defined in eqn (10) and λ 0 is the reorganization energy for a system with only one donor and one acceptor molecule. λ 0 was set to 0.25 eV, based on calculations of organic donor–acceptor pairs reported in literature. 32 We discuss the (modest) effect of changing λ 0 within a plausible range 0.15–0.40 eV in the results section. This scaling of the reorganization energy with the localization length is valid as long as the system does not form small polarons, a situation that is likely for the most common high mobility materials. 23,27
 ###### 
From cou.: 105 If we indicate with k(n)→(m) the rate constant for the process from Ψ(n)FE to Ψ(m)CT, the total rate for the process of generating any CT state can be expressed as:Where , with kBT being the thermal energy. The Boltzmann factor implies that we are assuming equilibrium among the FE electronic states. The initial and final states are very weakly coupled (see below for a justification) and the rate constant can be evaluated from the theory of non-adiabatic electron transfer reactions.31 The electron transfer is accompanied by a deformation in the equilibrium geometry of the molecule which is quantified by the parameter λ, known as the reorganization energy. If the nuclear modes can be treated classically the rate of charge transfer can be expressed by the Marcus equation:31where Vnm is the electronic coupling between the initial and final states. In writing eqn (13) we have noted that the reorganization energy λm depends on the final state states m (depending on the localization of the charge the reorganization energy may change). The combination of the two factors containing the term λm are normally referred to as the Franck–Condon factor. When the reorganization energy in the molecular crystals is decomposed according to the nuclear modes that contribute to it,32 it turns out that more than half of the reorganization energy is due to high frequency modes that cannot be treated classically. A more general expression taking into account the quantum nature of nuclear modes can be used but, as we will see in the result session, this is not really needed.
From Soup: 105 Table 1 summarizes the parameters used in the model, or their range when a range was used. The bottom of the excitonic band for a large cluster will be at E ex − 4| J | and this value should be greater than zero (the energy of separated D + and A − ) in order to have charge separation thermodynamically favoured for any choice of the other parameters. We have therefore set J = 0.06 eV, based on a typical excitonic coupling between organic crystals 36 and E ex = 0.25 eV. We have also considered narrower ( E ex = 0.13 eV, J = 0.03 eV) and broader ( E ex = 0.37 eV, J = 0.09 eV) excitonic bands above E = 0 as reported in the results section. Instead, it is probably not useful to consider excitonic bands at much higher energy (as in real devices that would dissipate too much energy and would probably involve further excited states of the acceptor).
 ###### 
From cou.: 106 The coupling Vnm can be obtained from eqn (6)–(8):
From Soup: 106 Considering the plausible range of parameters suitable for organic solar cell interfaces, it is already evident that the reaction that brings a Frenkel exciton at the bottom of the excitonic band ( E ( n ) FE ∼ [0.01 − 0.1] eV) into a strongly bound charge transfer state ( E ( m ) CT ∼ −1 eV) is always occurring in the Marcus inverted region, i.e. where E ( m ) CT − E ( m ) FE + λ m < 0. This fact is essentially determined by the size of typical organic molecules (setting boundaries to both the reorganization energy and the Coulombic interaction) and the low dielectric constant of the medium. In the Marcus inverted region the reaction is faster for smaller values of E ( m ) FE − E ( m ) CT , i.e. it is to be expected that the Frenkel exciton will not dissociate to form the most stable CT state, but a CT state closer in energy to the initial Frenkel state.
 ###### 
From cou.: 107 Except when we have very small clusters of 1–4 sites, or when we consider very localized states, we have generally , i.e. the coupling Vnm is always sufficiently small enough to allow the use of a perturbative expression, such as eqn (13). It is evident from eqn (13)–(14) that the parameter VDA will only modulate the final rate (through its square) but has otherwise no effect on the physics that we wish to describe. For this reason VDA was set to the physically plausible value of 0.08 eV and left unchanged.
From Soup: 107 Before studying the charge separation rate for different system parameters it is convenient to consider in detail the process of charge separation from the lowest energy FE state, which we can denote as Ψ (1) FE . The total rate of charge separation from this state is and the probability that the system is found in state Ψ ( m ) FE after the charge separation has taken place is k (1)→( m ) / k (1)→ All . Therefore, the probability of having a given electronic energy after the charge separation process can be computed as:
 ###### 
From cou.: 108 The reorganization energy is smaller for more delocalized states and it is approximately inversely proportional to the size of the system.33 This has been verified computationally for polymers of different lengths,34 for polyacenes of different sizes35 and for a large set of conjugated molecules.33 To incorporate this effect in the model we assumed that, for the computation of the rate k(n)→(m), λm decreases with the increase of delocalization of the charge in the CT state as λm = λ0/P(m), where P(m) is the number of molecules that share a positive or a negative charge as defined in eqn (10) and λ0 is the reorganization energy for a system with only one donor and one acceptor molecule. λ0 was set to 0.25 eV, based on calculations of organic donor–acceptor pairs reported in literature.32 We discuss the (modest) effect of changing λ0 within a plausible range 0.15–0.40 eV in the results section. This scaling of the reorganization energy with the localization length is valid as long as the system does not form small polarons, a situation that is likely for the most common high mobility materials.23,27
From Soup: 108 Fig. 4a compares the function P ( E ) with DOS CT ( E ) for the CT states. The key observation from this comparison is that the charge separation process selects states around E ∼ 0 and is not correlated at all with the DOS of the CT states. The rate (see eqn (13) and below) is determined by two terms: the coupling | V mn | 2 , which roughly decreases with increasing the energy, and the Franck–Condon factor, that has a maximum for E ( m ) CT − E (1) FE + λ m ∼ 0.
 ###### 
From cou.: 109 Table 1 summarizes the parameters used in the model, or their range when a range was used. The bottom of the excitonic band for a large cluster will be at Eex − 4|J| and this value should be greater than zero (the energy of separated D+ and A−) in order to have charge separation thermodynamically favoured for any choice of the other parameters. We have therefore set J = 0.06 eV, based on a typical excitonic coupling between organic crystals36 and Eex = 0.25 eV. We have also considered narrower (Eex = 0.13 eV, J = 0.03 eV) and broader (Eex = 0.37 eV, J = 0.09 eV) excitonic bands above E = 0 as reported in the results section. Instead, it is probably not useful to consider excitonic bands at much higher energy (as in real devices that would dissipate too much energy and would probably involve further excited states of the acceptor).
