From cou.: 110 Considering the plausible range of parameters suitable for organic solar cell interfaces, it is already evident that the reaction that brings a Frenkel exciton at the bottom of the excitonic band (E(n)FE ∼ [0.01 − 0.1] eV) into a strongly bound charge transfer state (E(m)CT ∼ −1 eV) is always occurring in the Marcus inverted region, i.e. where E(m)CT − E(m)FE + λm < 0. This fact is essentially determined by the size of typical organic molecules (setting boundaries to both the reorganization energy and the Coulombic interaction) and the low dielectric constant of the medium. In the Marcus inverted region the reaction is faster for smaller values of E(m)FE − E(m)CT, i.e. it is to be expected that the Frenkel exciton will not dissociate to form the most stable CT state, but a CT state closer in energy to the initial Frenkel state.
From Soup: 110 This coupling decreases with increasing energy because low energy states are near the interface and therefore strongly coupled with the CT state (see Fig. 3c and eqn (14) ). Fig. 4b shows that this decrease is approximately exponential at sufficiently large energies.
