From cou.: 119 P
From Soup: 119 In Fig. 3a we have seen that the effect of the coupling V D (= V A ) was to broaden the DOS CT . However, this effect is not particularly important for the computation of the k (1)→All rate of charge separation. More important is that CT states at the energy where the charge transfer takes place are more delocalized for larger V D , and, therefore, the coupling between these states and the Frenkel exciton is larger. Fig. 4b shows that for E > −0.2 eV (where the CT actually takes place) the average square coupling V 2 ( E ) increases with increasing the coupling V D . Consequently the rate of charge separation increases for increased values of V D , as reported in Fig. 5 . The interesting result is therefore that the donor and acceptor materials with broader bands (smaller effective masses) will facilitate not only the transport of holes and electrons, but also the formation of charge separated states.
 ###### 
From cou.: 120 E
From Soup: 120 Another interesting point is that the charge separation process does not involve low energy bound CT states at the interface. The fact that these bound CT states can be more or less delocalized depending on the value of V D 10 is not of direct relevance for the problem of charge separation. In realistic situations, if the band widths of the donor or acceptor are too small, the charge separation rate can be too slow and the exciton will more likely relax to the ground state without generating charges.
 ###### 
From cou.: 121 The Franck–Condon energy dependence dominates over the energy dependence of the effective coupling and the majority of the CT states are formed closer to the maximum of the Franck–Condon factor (shifted to lower energies because of the exponential decrease of the coupling). Essentially all the results presented in this section can be understood in terms of the contrasting energy dependence of the two functions V2(E) and F(E) that contribute to the charge separation rate.
From Soup: 121 Fig. 5 presents a comparison of the rates k TOT and k (1)→All for different values of V D to show that the two rates are only marginally different. This happens because the charge separation occurs from states at the bottom of the excitonic band. Consequently, the width of the excitonic band (associated to the exciton effective mass and the parameter J ) is not expected to be a crucial parameter. To verify this fact we report in the same figure the total rate for V D = 0.06 eV and with excitonic bands 50% broader or narrower: the total rate is essentially unaffected by the exciton band-width.
 ###### 
From cou.: 122 In Fig. 3a we have seen that the effect of the coupling VD (=VA) was to broaden the DOSCT. However, this effect is not particularly important for the computation of the k(1)→All rate of charge separation. More important is that CT states at the energy where the charge transfer takes place are more delocalized for larger VD, and, therefore, the coupling between these states and the Frenkel exciton is larger. Fig. 4b shows that for E > −0.2 eV (where the CT actually takes place) the average square coupling V2(E) increases with increasing the coupling VD. Consequently the rate of charge separation increases for increased values of VD, as reported in Fig. 5. The interesting result is therefore that the donor and acceptor materials with broader bands (smaller effective masses) will facilitate not only the transport of holes and electrons, but also the formation of charge separated states.
From Soup: 122 Slightly more important is the energy position of the lowest excitonic band edge, which determines the initial state energy. Consistent with the charge separation occurring in the inverted Marcus region, the charge separation rate (square symbol in Fig. 5 ) decreases when the exciton band energy is shifted upwards. However, as we noted above, these parameters cannot be set freely as an excitation energy too low will make the charge separation process thermodynamically unfavourable and an excitation energy too high will make the charge separation process too energy wasteful.
 ###### 
From cou.: 123 Another interesting point is that the charge separation process does not involve low energy bound CT states at the interface. The fact that these bound CT states can be more or less delocalized depending on the value of VD10 is not of direct relevance for the problem of charge separation. In realistic situations, if the band widths of the donor or acceptor are too small, the charge separation rate can be too slow and the exciton will more likely relax to the ground state without generating charges.
From Soup: 123 It is illustrative to compute the total rate of charge separation k TOT for different shapes of the donor–acceptor cluster ( Fig. 6 ). We considered for example clusters with n x = 4 and n z varying from 1 to 12 (see inset in the same figure). For thin interfaces (1 < n z < 3) k TOT increases with the increase of the cluster size. This is because the cluster is too thin to develop high energy delocalized CT states and the rate is decreased by an unfavourable Franck–Condon factor. When the clusters are thicker than n z = 4, k TOT does not change much but decreases as the size of the cluster increases. This is because, for larger clusters, the delocalized exciton is less coupled with the CT state (it is more “diluted”). It is remarkable that this decrease is so slow, i.e. if the exciton is delocalized, the formation of charge separated states may happen when the “centre” of the exciton is many layers away from the interface. This is in strong contrast with the view that an exciton should be localized at the interface to be split into free charges. Of course, in practice, an exciton cannot be unlimitedly delocalized, but delocalization over tens or hundreds of molecules seems to be the most consistent with the available spectroscopic data. 37,38
 ###### 
From cou.: 124 Fig. 5 presents a comparison of the rates kTOT and k(1)→All for different values of VD to show that the two rates are only marginally different. This happens because the charge separation occurs from states at the bottom of the excitonic band. Consequently, the width of the excitonic band (associated to the exciton effective mass and the parameter J) is not expected to be a crucial parameter. To verify this fact we report in the same figure the total rate for VD = 0.06 eV and with excitonic bands 50% broader or narrower: the total rate is essentially unaffected by the exciton band-width.
From Soup: 124 Similar calculations repeated with fixed small n z and variable n x give qualitatively similar results (not shown), i.e. what promotes efficient charge separation is the availability of CT states at the right energy and it is equivalent if the hole and electrons in these states are separated along the z or the x direction. In more realistic systems the bandwidth along the x and z direction is different and one can think that broader bands in the z directions are the most favourable to prevent charge recombination. Very interesting, these ideas begin to be explored experimentally, for example with time-resolved two- photon photoemission. 39
 ###### 
From cou.: 125 Slightly more important is the energy position of the lowest excitonic band edge, which determines the initial state energy. Consistent with the charge separation occurring in the inverted Marcus region, the charge separation rate (square symbol in Fig. 5) decreases when the exciton band energy is shifted upwards. However, as we noted above, these parameters cannot be set freely as an excitation energy too low will make the charge separation process thermodynamically unfavourable and an excitation energy too high will make the charge separation process too energy wasteful.
