From cou.: 126 It is illustrative to compute the total rate of charge separation kTOT for different shapes of the donor–acceptor cluster (Fig. 6). We considered for example clusters with nx = 4 and nz varying from 1 to 12 (see inset in the same figure). For thin interfaces (1 < nz < 3) kTOT increases with the increase of the cluster size. This is because the cluster is too thin to develop high energy delocalized CT states and the rate is decreased by an unfavourable Franck–Condon factor. When the clusters are thicker than nz = 4, kTOT does not change much but decreases as the size of the cluster increases. This is because, for larger clusters, the delocalized exciton is less coupled with the CT state (it is more “diluted”). It is remarkable that this decrease is so slow, i.e. if the exciton is delocalized, the formation of charge separated states may happen when the “centre” of the exciton is many layers away from the interface. This is in strong contrast with the view that an exciton should be localized at the interface to be split into free charges. Of course, in practice, an exciton cannot be unlimitedly delocalized, but delocalization over tens or hundreds of molecules seems to be the most consistent with the available spectroscopic data.37,38
From Soup: 126 The expression on the right hand side is just a Fermi Golden rule expression that would describe the charge separation if this were an entirely electronic process with no contribution from the nuclear degrees of freedom. The 8 × 8(×2) cluster that was used to illustrate the results in this paper is already very close to this minimum. Fig. 7 shows the rate computed for a range of values of λ 0 , including the limit λ 0 → 0 (until numerical errors becomes important). Maybe surprisingly, the reorganization energy that dramatically affects the charge transfer rate in single pairs of donor and acceptor is of modest importance for the system containing a cluster of donor and acceptor molecules: the charge separation rate in the limit λ 0 → 0 is only half of that computed with the reference value used in this paper ( λ 0 = 0.25 eV). This fact suggests that, although the process of charge separation in these interfaces has been principally considered a “chemical” process involving nuclear reorganization, it is to a large extent a purely electronic process and can be described to a good degree of accuracy by a purely electronic Hamiltonian. Also for this reason we did not present the results where eqn (13) is improved to take into account the quantum nature of some vibrations.
 ###### 
From cou.: 127 Similar calculations repeated with fixed small nz and variable nx give qualitatively similar results (not shown), i.e. what promotes efficient charge separation is the availability of CT states at the right energy and it is equivalent if the hole and electrons in these states are separated along the z or the x direction. In more realistic systems the bandwidth along the x and z direction is different and one can think that broader bands in the z directions are the most favourable to prevent charge recombination. Very interesting, these ideas begin to be explored experimentally, for example with time-resolved two-photon photoemission.39
From Soup: 127 We have studied a minimal model of the donor–acceptor interface encountered in organic solar cells to investigate the nature of the most likely charge transfer state formed from the dissociation of an exciton in the donor. The main findings of this work can be summarized as follows:
 ###### 
From cou.: 128 As the cluster becomes larger the reorganization energy becomes smaller. In the limit of λm → 0 the expression of the rate changes radically becoming:
From Soup: 128 (1) Excitons do not generate strongly bound hole-electron pairs, but relatively delocalized charge transfer states with energy very close to the energy of free holes and electrons. These states are kinetically more accessible from the exciton state and very close in structure to the free hole and electron states.
 ###### 
From cou.: 129 The expression on the right hand side is just a Fermi Golden rule expression that would describe the charge separation if this were an entirely electronic process with no contribution from the nuclear degrees of freedom. The 8 × 8(×2) cluster that was used to illustrate the results in this paper is already very close to this minimum. Fig. 7 shows the rate computed for a range of values of λ0, including the limit λ0 → 0 (until numerical errors becomes important). Maybe surprisingly, the reorganization energy that dramatically affects the charge transfer rate in single pairs of donor and acceptor is of modest importance for the system containing a cluster of donor and acceptor molecules: the charge separation rate in the limit λ0 → 0 is only half of that computed with the reference value used in this paper (λ0 = 0.25 eV). This fact suggests that, although the process of charge separation in these interfaces has been principally considered a “chemical” process involving nuclear reorganization, it is to a large extent a purely electronic process and can be described to a good degree of accuracy by a purely electronic Hamiltonian. Also for this reason we did not present the results where eqn (13) is improved to take into account the quantum nature of some vibrations.
From Soup: 129 (2) The most relevant molecular parameter that affects the rate of exciton dissociation is the electronic coupling between donor orbitals and acceptor orbitals, i.e. the band widths of the donor and acceptor materials. These parameters are important, not because they generate more delocalized CT states at the interface (which do not play any role in the charge separation process), but because they increase the effective coupling between the initial Frenkel exciton state and the final charge transfer (delocalized) state.
 ###### 
From cou.: 130 We have studied a minimal model of the donor–acceptor interface encountered in organic solar cells to investigate the nature of the most likely charge transfer state formed from the dissociation of an exciton in the donor. The main findings of this work can be summarized as follows:
From Soup: 130 (3) The process of charge separation is, to a large extent, an electronic process and a very similar physics can be described neglecting the role of nuclear motions altogether. This happens because the delocalization of hole and electron dramatically decreases the coupling with the nuclear degrees of freedom.
 ###### 
From cou.: 131 (1) Excitons do not generate strongly bound hole-electron pairs, but relatively delocalized charge transfer states with energy very close to the energy of free holes and electrons. These states are kinetically more accessible from the exciton state and very close in structure to the free hole and electron states.
From Soup: 131 Setting aside the many idealizations present in our model, whose relevance will be investigated in future works, the key difference between the presented description and the commonly accepted picture is that we did not use a single electron approximation to describe the charge separation process. It is customary in solid state physics to consider all charge transfer processes as occurring by electron transfer from one orbital to another, with the energy difference of the process given by the energy difference between the initial and final orbital energy. This single electron picture ( e.g. in Fig. 1a ) is accurate if we can assume that the energy of an electron is not affected by the occupation of the other orbitals, but this is clearly not true for the charge transfer state where the hole and electron wavefunctions generated by a single Frenkel exciton are entangled. The band diagram of holes and electrons is not at all representative of the process of charge separation which needs to be described in term of states . Once we have described the process as a mostly electronic process involving two sets of states ( Fig. 1b ) we made considerable progress and realized that there is no real kinetic barrier for the generation of free changes. Crucially, we have considered all charge transfer states, not just the ones that are generally assumed to be important and this is the main departure from other state-based models. The scheme of Fig. 1b remains valid if we move from the idealized situation described in this paper to a more realistic interface, involving disorder and more localized states, a situation that was investigated in ref. 19 . The problem of explaining the efficient generation of free carriers in organic solar cells seems now really manageable if the few steps above are taken.
 ###### 
From cou.: 132 (2) The most relevant molecular parameter that affects the rate of exciton dissociation is the electronic coupling between donor orbitals and acceptor orbitals, i.e. the band widths of the donor and acceptor materials. These parameters are important, not because they generate more delocalized CT states at the interface (which do not play any role in the charge separation process), but because they increase the effective coupling between the initial Frenkel exciton state and the final charge transfer (delocalized) state.
From Soup: 132 A number of recent experimental evidences seem to support the view of charge separation proposed in this paper. The necessity of a sufficiently large cluster of acceptors to promote charge separation was proposed by the Eindhoven group 40 and the importance of highly crystalline interfaces to promote delocalization has been highlighted a few times for polymer solar cells. 8,41 The temperature independent generation of CT states measured by many authors 15,42,43 is also fully consistent with the picture proposed in this paper, where the role of nuclear motions becomes marginal and the charge transfer happens by population transfer between quasi degenerate Frenkel and CT states.
 ###### 
From cou.: 133 (3) The process of charge separation is, to a large extent, an electronic process and a very similar physics can be described neglecting the role of nuclear motions altogether. This happens because the delocalization of hole and electron dramatically decreases the coupling with the nuclear degrees of freedom.
From Soup: 133 There are two directions of further investigation suggested by this work. First, one should relax some of the approximations made to reduce the number of parameters of the model ( e.g. V D = V A , square lattice arrangement, identical coupling along the x or y direction) and substitute these with realistic evaluations for systems with known morphology at the interface. Secondly, having realized that there is a strong coupling between exciton delocalization and charge separation dynamics, it becomes even more important to look again at the source of exciton localization in molecular crystals (and other organic semiconductors). While it was traditionally thought that the exciton migration and exciton dissociation process in organic photovoltaics can be considered independently, this and other works 19 suggest that the dynamics of the exciton and its dissociation into hole and electron are not really separable.
 ###### 
From cou.: 134 Setting aside the many idealizations present in our model, whose relevance will be investigated in future works, the key difference between the presented description and the commonly accepted picture is that we did not use a single electron approximation to describe the charge separation process. It is customary in solid state physics to consider all charge transfer processes as occurring by electron transfer from one orbital to another, with the energy difference of the process given by the energy difference between the initial and final orbital energy. This single electron picture (e.g. in Fig. 1a) is accurate if we can assume that the energy of an electron is not affected by the occupation of the other orbitals, but this is clearly not true for the charge transfer state where the hole and electron wavefunctions generated by a single Frenkel exciton are entangled. The band diagram of holes and electrons is not at all representative of the process of charge separation which needs to be described in term of states. Once we have described the process as a mostly electronic process involving two sets of states (Fig. 1b) we made considerable progress and realized that there is no real kinetic barrier for the generation of free changes. Crucially, we have considered all charge transfer states, not just the ones that are generally assumed to be important and this is the main departure from other state-based models. The scheme of Fig. 1b remains valid if we move from the idealized situation described in this paper to a more realistic interface, involving disorder and more localized states, a situation that was investigated in ref. 19. The problem of explaining the efficient generation of free carriers in organic solar cells seems now really manageable if the few steps above are taken.
